library(tidyverse)

Load the Data

We will use two separate data sets for this homework.

The first data set represent sightings of grizzly bears (Ursos arctos) in Alaska.

  1. Load the grizzly data and evaluate its structure.
grizzly <- read_csv("data/bear-sightings.csv")

  1. Use the range of the latitude and longitude to build an appropriate bounding box for your map.
lat <- c(55.02, 70.37)
long <- c(-166.2, -131.3)
bbox <- make_bbox(long, lat, f = 0.03)
  1. Load a map from stadiamaps in a stamen_terrain projection and display the map. Hint: use zoom=5.
register_stadiamaps("df7d4b33-d5e1-49bf-94f8-d32a109c561f", write = FALSE)
grizzly_map <- get_stadiamap(bbox, maptype = "stamen_terrain", zoom=5)
## ℹ © Stadia Maps © Stamen Design © OpenMapTiles © OpenStreetMap contributors.
ggmap(grizzly_map)

  1. Build a final map that overlays the recorded observations of grizzly bears in Alaska.
ggmap(grizzly_map) + #using layers not pipes
  theme_linedraw()+
  geom_point(data = grizzly, aes(longitude, latitude), size=0.7, color = "red") +
  labs(x= "Longitude", y= "Latitude", title="Bear Sightings")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))
